latestIgtvVideos.title: #fussyisfantastic
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
The moment I came across this video in @kareenakapoorkhan 's  Instagram , I was glad to relate  myself with every fussy mom. Indeed moms should be fussy because they are "mom" and no one could care more for the child than her .  Like these moms, I still remember last year when Corona was at its peak , I didnt let my kid meet any of our relatives coming to our home until and unless they have completed their quarantine period.  I was labelled as rude but deep down my heart I knew that my only priority was to keep my child safe. 
So when , i saw this video by @firstcryindia,  I felt immense respect for myself and every fussy mom who do their best for their kids. Thank you @firstcryindia for recognising our efforts and I can proudly say that #fussyisfantastic and yes I am one of them.
I am sure most of the moms can relate with this.Do let me know which moment on the film you can relate to the most. 

In collaboration with @firstcryindia

latestPosts.caption:
Manali Itinerary 

Day 1: Arrive in Manali and check into your hotel.  If time permits (rarely 😭)Enjoy a delicious Himachali dinner at a local restaurant. Try some local dishes like Siddu (steamed bread), Kullu Trout, and Chha Gosht (lamb curry).

Day 2: Manali Local Sightseeing
* a)Visit the Hidimba Devi Temple, a beautiful wooden temple dedicated to the wife of Bhima from the Mahabharata epic.
* b) Visit clubhouse for shopping and riverside adventure.
* c)take a stroll along the Mall Road, the bustling main street lined with shops, cafes. d)Visit the Vashisht Temple, a hot spring temple located in the old Manali village.  e)Explore the Tibetan Market, a vibrant market selling handicrafts, souvenirs, and local clothing. 
  
Day 3: Atal Tunnel and Sissu + Nehru Kund
* Morning: Take an exciting drive through the magnificent Atal Tunnel, a marvel of engineering that cuts through the Pir Panjal Range and significantly reduces travel time to Lahaul. Reach the picturesque village of Sissu, nestled along the Chandra River. Enjoy the stunning scenery and adventure activities, take a walk by the river, 
* visit the Nehru Kund, (while returning)a natural spring believed to have medicinal properties.  
Day 4: Naggar Castle, Manikaran & Kasol
* Morning: Drive to the charming hill town of Naggar and explore the Naggar Castle, a 15th-century fortress offering breathtaking views of the valley.
* Continue to Manikaran, a hot spring village famous for its geothermal waters. Take a dip in the hot springs, visit the Shiva temple and Manikaran Sahib Gurudwara. Then Head to Kasol, a laid-back village known for its hippie vibe and beautiful scenery.
Day 5: Departure
* Morning: Bid farewell to Manali and then on the way  You can do some shopping and adventure activities in Kullu too🤩. 

I hope this detailed itinerary helps you plan your Manali adventure! Have a wonderful time!

latestPosts.caption:
Winters in Manali can be harsh  and sometimes unbearable 🥶🥶especially if you are from southern part of the country. 
Hence, I am sharing few tips specially for parents as I saw many kids getting sick or feeling  uncomfortable in Sissu and parents had to return back due to kid/s condition. 
👉Book your accommodation in a centrally heated property.
👉If you’re traveling from a low-altitude region, it’s important to give your body time to acclimatize to the high altitude of Manali. Also,drink plenty of fluids.

👉Don’t try to pack too much into your itinerary, as young children get tired quickly.

👉Manali offers plenty of opportunities for outdoor activities .However, these activities may not be suitable for all children. Choose activities that are safe and age-appropriate.
👉Try to reach Sissu or any area with Snow/ Snow activities after 10: 00 am . Many parents reached Sissu around 8-9:00 am fearing Jam, but the kids got uncomfortable due to insufficient sunlight at that moment.
👉There are washrooms in Sissu but its too far from the activity area  and Most importantly, they were too dirty without any cleanliness and hygiene. Its better to use washrooms  on the way (near Atal Tunnel ).
👉Do not Forget your gloves, its a must.
👉If you are visiting during morning hours, check your rented boots twice ‘coz it will be “Killer” cold. Try to heat your legs or at least the boots by taking it near to fireplace/heater/similar things. Please don’t take this lightly,  the pain is real.

There are sunsets—and then there’s Uluwatu.

Perched dramatically on a cliff 70 meters above the Indian Ocean, Uluwatu Temple in Bali offers one of the most breathtaking sunset views I’ve ever witnessed. As the golden hour approaches, the sky transforms into a canvas of oranges, purples, and soft pinks, casting a magical glow over the ancient sea temple.

Waves crash below, monkeys roam the grounds, and the distant chants of the traditional Kecak fire dance echo through the air, adding a mystical touch to the already spiritual atmosphere.

If you’re ever in Bali, make time to witness this moment. Come for the view, stay for the feeling—it’s unforgettable.

📍Uluwatu Temple, Bali
🕕 Best time to visit: Around 5 PM to catch the sunset and the Kecak performance
💡 Tip: Watch your belongings—the monkeys are adorable but sneaky!

When Bali’s rain changed our plans, we found beauty in the unexpected! 🌧✨
Skipped Nusa Penida and explored the magical Alas Harum instead—complete with jungle views, sky swings, and a dreamy photoshoot backdrop. 📸🌿
Wrapped up the day wandering through the colorful lanes of Ubud Art Market and ended it with a soul-satisfying Japanese dinner. 🍣💫
Sometimes, detours lead to the best memories. 🫶

Bali Day 5 🇮🇩✨
Started the day with a peaceful visit to Ulun Danu Beratan Temple, floating on the calm waters of Lake Beratan in North Bali 🌿🛕 Then we explored the stunning Tanah Lot Temple, perched on a rock in the middle of the sea 🌊 – truly one of Bali’s most iconic spots! Wrapped up the day with a chill dinner in beautiful Ubud 🌺🍽️
If you’re planning your Bali itinerary, these two temples are a must-see!
